This notebook does some preliminary comparisons of SingleR results obtained with these two versions of the NBAtlas (aggregated) reference:

  • NE-combined: The reference has a single category for all Neuroendocrine (NE) cells
  • NE-separated: The reference has two categories, Neuroendocrine and Neuroendocrine-tumor (NE-tumor) where the latter are NE cells which are part of the paperâs âtumor zoomâ subset and were explicitly classified as malignant

This notebook explores whether Neuroendocrine should be a single label or have the two separated categories. On one hand, these different categories might indicate different tumor states or highly-similar normal cells. However, per direct correspondence with the NBAtlas authors, it is probably more likely that any different signal associated with the malignant cells vs other NE cells is driven by technical reasons such as data quality, and not biological signal.

The goal of this notebook is to briefly look at the difference in cell type assignments between these two reference options to determine whether to proceed with a separated or combined NE category of cells, with the null that we should use the combined reference unless there is a compelling difference between the results.

Compare trained SingleR models

In this section, we will compare some of the marker genes identified in the trained SingleR models directly. When training a model as we have done here, SingleR performs pairwise comparisons to identify marker genes as the top 10 upregulated genes for each label compared to each other label.

Intersecting NE marker genes in the separated model

Weâll first look at the NE-separated model which has two categories for Neuroendocrine (NE) and Neuroendocrine-tumor (NE-tumor). Weâll pull out the marker genes for each and ask how similar they are. In other words, weâll ask if there is overlap between:

  • Marker genes upregulated in NE compared to each other cell type
  • Marker genes upregulated in NE-tumor compared to each other cell type
# markers upregulated NE compared to other cell types in the separated model
ne_markers <- model_separated$markers$full$Neuroendocrine

# markers upregulated NE-tumor compared to other cell types in the separated model
ne.tumor_markers <- model_separated$markers$full$`Neuroendocrine-tumor`

Below we print the intersection of these two sets of marker genes for each cell type comparison:

separated_cell_types <- names(ne_markers)
non_neuro_cell_types <- separated_cell_types[!(stringr::str_detect(separated_cell_types, "Neuro"))]

intersecting_marker_genes <- non_neuro_cell_types |>
  purrr::set_names() |>
  purrr::map(
    \(cell_type) {
      intersect(
        ne_markers[[cell_type]],
        ne.tumor_markers[[cell_type]]
      )
    }
  )

# Print as data frame so it doesn't print double
intersecting_marker_genes |>
  purrr::map(
    \(x) data.frame(genes = paste(sort(x), collapse = ", "))
  ) |>
  purrr::list_rbind(names_to = "cell_type") |>
  # add column with gene count
  dplyr::mutate(n_genes = stringr::str_count(genes, ",") + 1) |>
  dplyr::select(cell_type, n_genes, gene_symbols = genes)

Most marker genes are actually the same for the NE and NE-tumor pairwise comparisons, indeed showing us that these categories are highly similar. The main exception is RBCs for which there are apparently very different gene lists for NE and NE-tumor. Moreover, the genes tend to be the same across cell types, which suggests these are probably more universal NE markers.

Expression of different NE marker genes in the separated model

Next, weâll pull out the distinct marker genes associated with NE and NE-tumor groups that are also not represented in the combined modelâs NE marker genes.

Weâll look at these genesâ expression in cells that were annotated as NE and NE-tumor by the separated model. We expect that these distributions will show some difference (since SingleR will find genes no matter what!) between annotated cell types NE and NE-tumor. If the magnitude of the difference is large, it suggests that separating NE into two groups may not be unreasonable. If the magnitude of the difference is small, it suggests that separating NE into two groups is oversplitting.

In the plot, each point represents gene expression in a given cell, and the black diamonds are the mean expression for that gene.

That said, note that there are likely very different numbers of cells labeled as NE and NE-tumor, which may influence how these plots are interpreted.

celltype_df |>
  dplyr::filter(stringr::str_detect(singler_label_separated, "Neuro")) |>
  dplyr::count(singler_label_separated)
combined_marker_genes <- model_combined$markers$full$Neuroendocrine |>
  purrr::reduce(c) |>
  unique()

cell_types <- names(ne_markers)
non_neuro_cell_types <- cell_types[!(stringr::str_detect(cell_types, "Neuro"))]

different_marker_genes <- non_neuro_cell_types |>
  purrr::set_names() |>
  purrr::map(
    \(cell_type) {
      # In NE but not in NE-tumor
      diff_genes_ne <- setdiff(
        ne_markers[[cell_type]],
        ne.tumor_markers[[cell_type]]
      )

      # In NE-tumor but not in NE
      diff_genes_ne.tumor <- setdiff(
        ne.tumor_markers[[cell_type]],
        ne_markers[[cell_type]]
      )

      return(
        list(
          "ne_only" = diff_genes_ne,
          "ne.tumor_only" = diff_genes_ne.tumor
        )
      )
    }
  ) |>
  # transpose so it is a list of two, "ne_only" and "ne.tumor_only",
  # each of which is a named list of marker genes for each cell type
  purrr::transpose() |>
  # collapse each nested list to remove cell types
  # keep only unique genes
  # remove any genes that are also in combined_marker_genes
  purrr::map(
    \(gene_list) {
      gene_vector <- gene_list |>
        purrr::reduce(c) |>
        unique()
      gene_vector[!(gene_vector %in% combined_marker_genes)]
    }
  )

# This final list are the genes uniquely upregulated in the NE and
# NE-tumor categories in the separated model

Compare separated to combined models

Next, weâll look at the NE marker genes between references and ask for a quick summary:

How many of the NE markers in the combined model (again, out of 10 total per cell type comparison!) are also included in the separated modelâs NE (or NE-tumor) marker gene lists?

combined_markers <- model_combined$markers$full$Neuroendocrine

combined_markers |>
  # only comparisons to other groups of cells
  purrr::discard_at("Neuroendocrine") |>
  purrr::imap(
    \(combined_marker_genes, cell_type) {
      separated_model_markers <- c(
        # upregulated in NE compared to cell_type
        ne_markers[[cell_type]],
        # upregulated in NE-tumor compared to cell-type
        ne.tumor_markers[[cell_type]]
      ) |> unique()

      # how many combined are in that separated list?
      sum(combined_marker_genes %in% separated_model_markers)
    }
  ) |>
  as.data.frame() |>
  t()

Here, we see that NE marker genes from the combined model are essentially entirely contained within the NE and/or NE-tumor categories of the separated model.

Conclusions

Based on a brief comparison of marker genes in the SingleR models, we see that:

  • In the separated model, marker genes that distinguish NE from other cell types and marker genes that distinguish NE-tumor from other cell types are highly similar.
    • These genes were identified in NBAtlas as NE marker genes as well
    • These genes tend to overlap with marker genes that distinguish NE from other cell types in the combined model
  • It is additionally worth noting that SingleR inference took much longer with the separated than combined model
